        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer56824236" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7080127262561144778">Without getting into any spoilers: this is a fictionalized account of the doomed Franklin expedition to find the Northwest Passage in 1845. It is about hubris, greed, strength during unspeakable adversity, and possibly redemption.<br/><br/>Oh, there&apos;s also a terrifying monster that they call The Thing on The Ice which is slowly killing everyone aboard the two ships.<br/><br/>It&apos;s <a href='https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2687.Dan_Simmons' title='Dan Simmons' rel='nofollow noopener'>Dan Simmons</a>, so he takes his time getting into the meat of the story (my dad said that he was telling three stories when he could have to</span>
  <span id="freeText7080127262561144778" style="display:none">Without getting into any spoilers: this is a fictionalized account of the doomed Franklin expedition to find the Northwest Passage in 1845. It is about hubris, greed, strength during unspeakable adversity, and possibly redemption.<br /><br />Oh, there's also a terrifying monster that they call The Thing on The Ice which is slowly killing everyone aboard the two ships.<br /><br />It's <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/2687.Dan_Simmons" title="Dan Simmons" rel="nofollow noopener">Dan Simmons</a>, so he takes his time getting into the meat of the story (my dad said that he was telling three stories when he could have told one) but I consider that to be a feature of his writing, rather than a bug.<br /><br />I absolutely loved this novel. In fact, I loved it so much, I read most of it during JoCoCruiseCrazy in the beginning of 2011, because I just couldn't put it down, even though I was in the middle of the Caribbean on an amazing cruise.</span>
